spans.text: poetic wake my string : A mortal Muse demands my lyre
NOR Phoebus , nor his tuneful choir , To notes poetic wake my string : A mortal Muse demands my lyre , OH , were she present while
the eagle-wing Of bright Imagination , first of Powers
to sing Strains not unworthy STUDLEY's charming bowers
Strains not unworthy STUDLEY's charming bowers
her best-loved seat , And Taste and Nature every power combine
The curious eye , entranced in wonder ,
with flowers Your fairy gardens on the Western shore , Or add fresh bloom to famed Alcinous' bowers ; Vain Greece , thy fabled Tempe boast no more
Refined or simple , natural or new , Compound together
end ? the labouring soul , Lost and bewildered in a world of sweets , Vainly attempts at once to grasp the whole
The bulfinch , linnet , nightingale , and thrush
Amid such beauties well content to dwell
Coursing each other to the seat they love
Where genial Freedom unrestrained commands , Where none are strangers
Whirled in the topsy-turvy wheel of state
a sacrifice of sense to pride
undistinguished mid the common throng , There many a hoary devotee of yore Awaked the skylark with his early song

its mouldering base and moss-grown head Threaten its final dissolution nigh
well ( for surely one day think we must ) That stately STUDLEY's pride must fall at last , And lovely BETSY's form submit to dust
